ont-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">If your Chicago condo faces south or west, you already know the problem: intense afternoon and midday sun that floods the room with glare, drives up cooling costs, and fades your furniture — all while you paid a premium for that skyline or lake view. The challenge is blocking the heat and glare without losing the view that makes the unit worth the price. This guide covers exactly which window treatments work for Chicago&#x27;s most sun-challenged orientations.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">The South/West Exposure Problem in Chicago</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Chicago high-rises, particularly in River North, Streeterville, South Loop, and West Loop, are concentrated in areas where south and west exposures receive the most direct solar radiation. A south-facing 20th-floor window receives 20–30% more direct sun annually than a north-facing window. West-facing units in River North or West Loop get the full force of Chicago&#x27;s summer afternoon sun — often combined with reflected heat off surrounding glass tower facades. Without proper window treatments, interior temperatures in these units can spike 10–15°F above ambient during peak sun hours, driving air conditioning costs significantly higher.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Solar Shades: The View-Preserving Solution</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">For south and west-facing condos where view preservation matters, solar shades are almost always the correct primary treatment. The key variable is openness factor — the percentage of light the weave allows through.</p><ul style=\"margin:0.75rem 0 0;padding:0;list-style:none;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.625rem\"><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>1% openness: Maximum solar heat and glare blockage, view is present but hazy — best for extreme south/west exposure</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>3% openness: Strong solar control, view is clearly visible but color-shifted — most popular for south-facing Chicago units</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>5% openness: Moderate solar control, excellent view clarity — good for west-facing rooms where afternoon glare is the primary issue</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>10% openness: Light shading and UV protection only — not recommended for Chicago south/west exposures</span></li></ul></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Fabric Color Matters More Than You Think</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">For south and west-facing Chicago condos, solar shade fabric color has a measurable impact on performance. Darker fabrics (charcoal, bronze, dark gray) absorb more heat and provide dramatically better glare control and outward view clarity compared to lighter fabrics at the same openness factor. A 3% charcoal solar shade outperforms a 3% white solar shade for view preservation and glare control by a significant margin. The tradeoff: darker fabrics absorb more heat before it enters the room, which works well in air-conditioned buildings but should be considered in non-AC units.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Motorized Shades: The Practical Choice for High-Rise</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">For south and west-facing condos in Chicago high-rises, motorized solar shades are a strong practical choice. The ability to lower shades at peak sun hours from your phone or on a schedule — without having to reach over furniture or operate manual controls at difficult window heights — is valuable when you&#x27;re adjusting shades multiple times per day as the sun moves. Motorized Somfy or Hunter Douglas PowerView systems integrate with Google Home, Amazon Alexa, and Apple HomeKit. For Chicago condo owners who travel frequently, motorized shades also provide security benefits by creating an occupied appearance.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Dual-Bracket Systems for Bedroom South/West Windows</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">South and west-facing bedroom windows in Chicago high-rises present a compound problem: you need solar control during the day and complete blackout for sleep, especially during long summer days when the sun sets after 8:30 PM and Chicago&#x27;s urban light pollution keeps the sky bright long after sunset. A dual-bracket system with a 3% solar shade on the front bracket and a blackout roller on the rear bracket is the standard solution for these windows. Both shades operate independently and provide complete coverage for every scenario.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Building Appearance Requirements</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Most Chicago high-rises with homeowner associations or building management requirements specify that window treatments must appear white, off-white, or neutral from the exterior. This requirement applies to south and west-facing units regardless of what interior color you prefer. Solar shades and roller shades are both available with white or natural backing fabrics that satisfy building requirements while allowing you to choose any interior-facing color. Always verify your building&#x27;s specific requirements before ordering — our team is familiar with the requirements in most major Chicago condo buildings and can confirm compliance.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Our Recommendation for South/West Chicago Condos</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Primary living areas: 3% openness solar shade in charcoal or bronze (preserves view, maximizes solar control). Bedrooms: dual-bracket system with 3% solar + blackout roller. All rooms: motorized operation if budget allows, manual cordless if not. Schedule a free in-home consultation and we&#x27;ll bring solar fabric samples to test against your actual windows at your specific floor height — the same shade can look dramatically different on the 5th floor vs. the 35th floor due to viewing angle and surrounding reflections.</p></div><div style=\"margin-top:3rem;padding:2rem;background:var(--surface-2);border-radius:var(--radius);border-left:4px solid var(--brand)\"><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.0625rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.5rem\">Ready for a free in-home consultation?</p><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:0.9375rem;line-height:1.6;margin-bottom:1rem\">We come to you, measure every window, and give you a written quote on the spot. Serving all Chicago neighborhoods.</p><div style=\"display:flex;gap:0.75rem;flex-wrap:wrap\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary\" style=\"font-size:0.9375rem\" href=\"/quote\">Book Free Consultation</a><a href=\"tel:+13123610908\" class=\"btn btn-secondary\" style=\"font-size:0.9375rem\">(312) 361-0908</a></div></div></div></article><section style=\"padding:3rem 1.5rem 4rem;background:var(--surface-2);border-top:1px solid var(--bor